      "id":"books/2013/oct/28/prisonomics-by-vicky-pryce-review",
      "sectionId":"books",
      "sectionName":"Books",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-28T09:00:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Prisonomics by Vicky Pryce – review",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/oct/28/prisonomics-by-vicky-pryce-review",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2013/oct/28/prisonomics-by-vicky-pryce-review",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"42",
        "trailText":"<p>Pryce's call for better conditions for female offenders would have benefited from a touch of contrition, writes <strong>Jonathan Aitken</strong></p>",
        "headline":"Prisonomics by Vicky Pryce – review",
        "body":"<p>All prisons exude an aura of sadness.  But the most poignant depths of the criminal justice system are surely to be found in the establishments that incarcerate women. Their plight is an unfashionable and underreported subject. So Vicky Pryce has done the state some service by writing about her own two-month journey through HMP's Holloway and East Sutton Park.</p><p>This book is partly a prison memoir and partly an economist's critique of the system. These two halves fit uneasily together.</p><p>Most prison writers (myself included) have turbulent tales to tell, raw in their own and their fellow inmates' emotions. But this narrative contains no echoes of the <em>cri de coeur</em> in Oscar Wilde's classic <em>De Profundis</em>. The author seems to skate along the surface of even the most difficult moments. When entering the chaos of&nbsp;overcrowded Holloway she describes the usually rather grisly reception procedures as \"smooth, humane and expertly carried out\". She encounters \"no animosity, sniping, bitching or negative treatment from anyone either among my fellow inmates or from the officers\". The Panglossian tone continues through the descriptive chapters, which have a surprisingly depersonalised lack of&nbsp;passion.</p><p>They portray a brave, controlled heroine who sheds no tears, expresses no regrets, preens herself in the mirror before being sentenced, sleeps well at night, admits that her greatest preoccupation in jail is an obsession with tidiness and congratulates herself on having achieved \"universal name recognition\" in the media. From such passages one begins to wonder whether her name should be Mrs Ice rather than Mrs Pryce.</p><p>Yet for all its personal detachment, this book does not lack fervour, even if its style displays the didactic zeal of a prison lecturer rather than the anguish of a prison sufferer.</p><p>Pryce argues her case capably, bolstered by a barrage of statistics that tell their own story. The 4,000 or so female prisoners in England and Wales each cost the taxpayer £56,000 a year. They account for one-third of the incidents of self-harm throughout the entire 88,000-strong jail population;  are mostly non-violent; have a 54% reoffending rate in the first year after their release (higher than male offenders); and by being in custody cause more than 17,000 annual separations of mothers from children.</p><p>Ninety six per cent of women prisoners serve their sentences in high- or medium-security jails. Not because they are dangerous, but because there are only 228 female places in open or Category D prisons. Vicky Pryce was one of the lucky 228. After four days in Holloway she was transported, after a hilarious breakdown of her prison van on the M20, to East Sutton Park (ESP).</p><p>This Elizabethan stately home set in 84 acres of parkland was more like Downton Abbey than a dungeon. It featured karaoke nights, bingo nights, Saturday walks in brilliant sunshine through the Kent countryside, a home farm and a butler's pantry. Only Lord Grantham and Dame Nellie Melba seem to have been missing from the cast.</p><p>Although there are comic moments such as the description of how \"the girls\" (the universal term for women prisoners) operated the erratic shower system, the backdrop of sadness at ESP is all pervasive. \"Most women offenders are victims as well as offenders,\" writes Pryce, \"and they have often offended precisely because they are victims.\"</p><p>Being the victim of a domineering male partner may well be the explanation of the crimes of many female prisoners, but it is not always an excuse for them. Pryce attacks \"an anachronistic archaic network of male judges who send far too many women to prison\", but the judiciary is the wrong target.</p><p>The problem has been better diagnosed by Baroness Corston in her excellent <a href=\"http://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;ved=0CDEQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.justice.gov.uk%2Fpublications%2Fdocs%2Fcorston-report-march-2007.pdf&amp;ei=djZgUtb0IeWd0AWb_4CgCg&amp;usg=AFQjCNGoR1ND8UM6bRG8RTw6IZrrGmWbVg&amp;sig2=W9-uI_4TrtI2PBvx6lcwVw&amp;bvm=bv.54176721,d.d2k\" title=\"\">2007 report</a>, which called for a completely new approach to the punishment of female offenders &nbsp;involving more rehabilitation and a network of small custodial centres across the country. Unfortunately the Corston report has been ignored by successive governments, probably on economic grounds.</p><p>Vicky Pryce convincingly argues the public expenditure case for alternatives to prison for women. Her voice is a welcome support to Jean Corston's cause, but it would have been a more effective one if <em>Prisonomics</em> had contained a single paragraph of regret, remorse or repentance for the author's own crime.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420298181|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|511ffe4b6191c24fb03b1dc976b9c32736c7dfb4 -->",
