        "newspaperPageNumber":"8",
        "trailText":"Chris Huhne's ex-wife says government plan to remove automatic right to television in cell is 'asking for trouble'",
        "headline":"Vicky Pryce: prison perks crackdown could lead to riots",
        "body":"<p>Vicky Pryce, the ex-wife of the former cabinet minister Chris Huhne, has said there will be serious riots if the government proceeds with plans to ban televisions in prisoners' cells.</p><p>The prominent economist, who was jailed along with Huhne for perverting the course of justice, attacked the coalition's crackdown on automatic perks offered in prison, saying it was \"just asking for trouble\".</p><p>Pryce gave the warning after writing a book about her time in prison, where she spent two months for taking her then husband's speeding points in a scandal that led to his resignation as the Liberal Democrat energy secretary.</p><p>\"There's very little else to do in prison but watch television. It's one of the very few things that these people have,\" she said. \"And if they take those away from their cells, as the government is saying it will do now, there will be riots, serious riots. And that is not an overstatement.</p><p>\"There is nothing else to occupy yourself with in prison – it is not a stimulating environment in the least. And once these new rules come into effect, they'll all go mad. From what I've seen from the inside, it's a foolish plan.\"</p><p>She made the remarks at the Cheltenham literature festival this month.</p><p>Under the government's proposals, all prisoners in England and Wales will initially have to wear uniforms, work longer hours and have to earn the right to have a televisions in their cells.</p><p>There will be a blanket ban on subscription television channels and access to 18-certificate DVDs. Prisoners who cause damage will be charged for the cost of repairs.</p><p>Speaking at the Cheltenham Literature Festival earlier this month, Pryce said: \"Chris Grayling [the justice secretary] announced this to much fanfare but I do not believe he has thought through the ramifications of this at all. It is just asking for trouble.\"</p><p>This year, Grayling ordered that all criminals would have to earn privileges, rather than have them removed for bad behaviour, in an attempt to counter the perception that prisoners' conditions are too comfortable. They will only be granted restricted access to cash and short visits to the gym.</p><p>At the time, Grayling said he wanted criminals' arrival in prison for the first time \"to be an experience that is not one they'd want to repeat … That means an environment where they arrive, standards are pretty basic and then they start to gain extras by contributing … and if they won't do it, then they can't expect to start gaining those privileges.\" Grayling disputed Pryce's comments, saying the policy \"is not a knee-jerk reaction\". He said: \"We have been working for six months to ensure that the scheme is implemented safely across the prison estate,\" he said. \"This is not about taking away TVs for no reason, it is about prisoners earning the right to watch them.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421143190|2013-11-05T11:03:51Z|aa3ffe3ff5506fd6dfaa341fba4998ace33a4ac1 -->",
